Preliminary Wrangling¶

The dataset represents all the bike trips in the database of the company BayWheels - which operates in the San Francisco Area, Oakland, Berkeley, and San Jos. This dataset does not require major cleaning and wrangling, except for a couple of datatype changes.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 519700 different log of bike rides. Most variables are numeric in nature, but the variables start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, should be (for now) considered categorical and nominal, since we cannot really perform any kind of mathematical operation with them.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The questions that are of the most interest to me are:

  • What are the most popular stations to start a trip?
  • How does the bike usage depend on the time of the day?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that the trip duration and trip frequency depend very much on the time of the day, in particular on the common working hours.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The duration_sec variable took on a large range of values with some radical outliers, so I looked at the data using a log transform. Under the transformation, the data looked unimodal, with one peak around 600 seconds (10 minutes).

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I we discuss further the outliers for duration_sec variable, they do not seem sur-real, but more likely to be really rare and quite exceptional in nature. One bike was rented for 80,000 seconds (more than 22 hours!), so I can only guess that it was either a technical issue or someone just forgot to bring it back.

plt.figure(figsize=[12,12])

bins_x = np.arange(df.start_station_longitude.min(), df.start_station_longitude.max()+0.01, 0.01)
ticks_x = np.arange(df.start_station_longitude.min(), df.start_station_longitude.max()+0.025, 0.025)

plt.hist2d(data = df, x = 'start_station_longitude', y = 'start_station_latitude', cmin = 0.5,
          bins = [bins_x, bins_y])
plt.xticks(ticks = ticks_x, labels = ticks_x, rotation = 45)
plt.yticks(ticks = ticks_y, labels = ticks_y)

plt.show()

This heatmap confirms the geographical clustering for the bikeshare system: there are three major clusters in the San Francisco Area. I took the middle points of each heatmap and put them into a search engine:

  • Cluster 1 - San Jos (37.320000, -121.890000)
  • Cluster 2 - Oakland / Berkeley (37.78000, -122.27000)
  • Cluster 3 - San Francisco (37.76000, -122.40000)

This assumption about 3 clusters is confirmed by the BayWheels internet site.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

There are clearly some observable differences between two groups of users: customers and subscribers. Customers tend to have longer trip durations than subscribers.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

At first, I did not plan to analyze latitudes and longitudes, but thanks to pyplot's heatmap functionality I managed to discover 3 geographical clusters, where we could perform multivariate analysis later on.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

At the beginning of the project, I was reluctant to use latitudes and longitudes because of their assumed uselessness. However, thanks to bulding multivariate models, I make some very important and useful conclusions: it seems that the lion's share of the biking activity happens in the Downtown San Francisco, where bikes are easily taken and out back after some short period of time. The activity on the outskirts are less frequent but trips are longer - meaning that these users mostly have long trips to and from the downtown.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

As I already stated - when I started the project, I did not think to use the geographical data at all, but it seems that we can use it in lots of ways, actually! Personally, it helped me draw the of San Francisco and get interesting observations from there!
